              <section class="prose">
                <h2>How this Canadian mortgage calculator works</h2>
                <p>
                  This tool is designed specifically for the Canadian mortgage
                  market. It models:
                </p>
                <ul>
                  <li>Blended principal-and-interest payments</li>
                  <li>
                    CMHC (or other insurer) mortgage default insurance on
                    high-ratio mortgages
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    Canadian payment frequencies, including accelerated options
                  </li>
                  <li>The federal mortgage stress test (qualifying rate)</li>
                </ul>

                <h3>1. Mortgage amount and CMHC insurance</h3>
                <p>First we calculate your base mortgage:</p>
                <div class="formula-box">
                  <p>
                    <strong>Base mortgage</strong> = Home price − Down payment
                  </p>
                </div>
                <p>
                  If your down payment is less than 20% of the purchase price,
                  the mortgage is considered
                  <strong>high-ratio</strong> and usually requires default
                  insurance from CMHC, Sagen or Canada Guaranty. The premium is
                  added to your mortgage amount.
                </p>
                <p>Typical premium brackets (subject to change by insurers):</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    Down payment 5% to &lt;10%: about <strong>4.00%</strong> of
                    mortgage
                  </li>
                  <li>10% to &lt;15%: about <strong>3.10%</strong></li>
                  <li>15% to &lt;20%: about <strong>2.80%</strong></li>
                  <li>
                    ≥20%: <strong>no insurance</strong> (conventional mortgage)
                  </li>
                </ul>
                <p>Our calculator uses these tiers to estimate the premium:</p>
                <div class="formula-box">
                  <p>
                    <strong>Insurance premium</strong> = Base mortgage × Premium
                    rate
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    <strong>Total mortgage</strong> = Base mortgage + Insurance
                    premium
                  </p>
                </div>

                <h3>2. Payment frequency and accelerated options</h3>
                <p>Canadian lenders commonly offer:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li><strong>Monthly</strong> – 12 payments per year</li>
                  <li><strong>Semi-monthly</strong> – 24 payments per year</li>
                  <li><strong>Bi-weekly</strong> – 26 payments per year</li>
                  <li><strong>Weekly</strong> – 52 payments per year</li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>Accelerated bi-weekly</strong> – 26 payments per
                    year, but each payment is half of the monthly amount
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>Accelerated weekly</strong> – 52 payments per year,
                    each payment is a quarter of the monthly amount
                  </li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                  Accelerated options effectively add one extra monthly payment
                  per year, which goes straight to principal and can
                  significantly reduce interest and amortization length.
                </p>

                <h3>3. Mortgage payment formula</h3>
                <p>
                  For a fixed rate over the term, the payment is calculated
                  using the standard loan formula:
                </p>
                <div class="formula-box">
                  <p>Let:</p>
                  <ul>
                    <li>\( P \) = mortgage amount (after insurance)</li>
                    <li>\( r \) = annual interest rate</li>
                    <li>\( m \) = number of payments per year</li>
                    <li>
                      \( n \) = total number of payments = amortization years ×
                      \( m \)
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                  <p>
                    Periodic interest rate: \( i = \dfrac{r}{100 \times m} \)
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    Payment per period: \[ \text{Payment} = P \times \frac{i(1 +
                    i)^n}{(1 + i)^n - 1} \]
                  </p>
                </div>
                <p>
                  For accelerated bi-weekly and weekly payments, we first
                  compute the <strong>equivalent monthly payment</strong>
                  and then divide it by 2 (bi-weekly) or 4 (weekly) to get the
                  accelerated amount.
                </p>

                <h3>4. Mortgage stress test</h3>
                <p>
                  To qualify for a mortgage in Canada, lenders must ensure you
                  can afford payments at the
                  <strong>higher</strong> of:
                </p>
                <ul>
                  <li>Your contract rate + 2 percentage points, or</li>
                  <li>The Bank of Canada qualifying rate</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Our calculator:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>Uses your entered stress-test rate if provided, or</li>
                  <li>Defaults to contract rate + 2%</li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                  We then recalculate the payment using the same formula but
                  with the higher qualifying rate.
                </p>

                <h3>5. Amortization schedule</h3>
                <p>The amortization schedule shows, for each payment:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>How much goes to <strong>interest</strong></li>
                  <li>How much goes to <strong>principal</strong></li>
                  <li>Your remaining balance after the payment</li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                  At the start of the mortgage, interest makes up a larger share
                  of each payment. Over time, as the balance shrinks, more of
                  each payment goes to principal.
                </p>

                <h2>Frequently asked questions about Canadian mortgages</h2>

                <h3>Is a 25-year or 30-year amortization better?</h3>
                <p>
                  A 25-year amortization has higher payments but much lower
                  total interest and is required for most insured (high-ratio)
                  mortgages. A 30-year amortization is usually only available
                  with at least 20% down and results in lower payments but
                  higher total interest. Use the calculator to compare both
                  scenarios.
                </p>

                <h3>How much do I need for a down payment in Canada?</h3>
                <ul>
                  <li>First C$500,000: minimum <strong>5%</strong></li>
                  <li>
                    Portion from C$500,000 to C$999,999: minimum
                    <strong>10%</strong>
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    Homes C$1,000,000 or more: minimum <strong>20%</strong> (no
                    CMHC insurance)
                  </li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                  Our calculator assumes a single down payment percentage on the
                  full price for simplicity, but you can adjust the down payment
                  to see how it affects insurance and payments.
                </p>

                <h3>What other costs should I budget for?</h3>
                <p>Beyond the mortgage payment, you should plan for:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    Property taxes (often paid with your mortgage in some
                    provinces)
                  </li>
                  <li>Heating costs and utilities</li>
                  <li>Condo fees (if applicable)</li>
                  <li>Home insurance</li>
                  <li>
                    Closing costs (legal fees, land transfer tax, title
                    insurance, etc.)
                  </li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                  The optional property tax and heating/condo fields let you
                  approximate your <strong>total monthly housing cost</strong>.
                </p>

                <h3>Fixed vs. variable rate in Canada</h3>
                <p>
                  A <strong>fixed-rate</strong> mortgage keeps the interest rate
                  constant for the term (e.g., 5 years), making payments
                  predictable. A <strong>variable-rate</strong> mortgage moves
                  with the lender’s prime rate. Some variable products keep the
                  payment fixed and adjust the amortization; others adjust the
                  payment. Our calculator assumes a constant rate over the full
                  amortization for comparison purposes.
                </p>

                <h3>How can I pay off my Canadian mortgage faster?</h3>
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    Choose an
                    <strong>accelerated bi-weekly or weekly</strong> payment
                    schedule
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    Increase your regular payment amount if your lender allows
                    it
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    Make lump-sum prepayments (often up to 10–20% of the
                    original principal per year)
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    Refinance to a lower rate when it makes sense, considering
                    penalties
                  </li>
                </ul>
